        introduction: "Calvi, the pearl of the Corsican Balagne, is one of the most enchanting destinations on the Isle of Beauty. Its massive Genoese citadel, rising from a rocky headland above a crescent-shaped bay of fine sand and pine groves, creates a breathtakingly beautiful scene revealed at the last bend in the road. The 95-kilometre taxi journey from Bastia crosses northern Corsica through magnificent mountain scenery before emerging onto the luminous Balagne coast. Calvi proudly claims to be Christopher Columbus's birthplace — a debated thesis passionately upheld by locals. The citadel houses the ruins of the explorer's supposed home, with rampart views spanning the entire bay and the Revellata peninsula. The Balagne, nicknamed the 'garden of Corsica', is a region of gentle hills covered with olive trees and citrus orchards, dotted with perched stone villages — Pigna, Sant'Antonino ranked among France's most beautiful villages, and Lumio immortalised by Laetitia Casta.",
